dismissalText.commentary: Cephas Zhuwao c Rankin b McCarthy 20 (18b 1x4 2x6 17m) SR: 111.11

dismissalComment.html: the Zhuwao show has ended ! He seemed troubled by McCarthy's slower deliveries. He perishes to another slower delivery as he has made up his mind to play a shot, regardless. The ball in on the off stump line and Zhuwao lofts it right into the outstretched hands of Rankin at long-on. Good bowling by McCarthy

dismissalComment.html: sees him coming down the track and pushes it through faster and wider. Mire is beaten by pace and line as he looks to get some bat on the ball as he is trotting down the track. Niall O'Brien collects the ball cleanly and whips the bails off. McBrine strikes in his first over

dismissalText.commentary: Hamilton Masakadza c †NJ O'Brien b Rankin 18 (24b 2x4 0x6 30m) SR: 75

dismissalComment.html: the relentless line does the trick! Short of a good length delivery outside the off stump. Masakadza, till now, was looking to get behind the line of these deliveries but there seems to be a lapse in concentration as he stays rooted to the crease and looks to get some bat on the ball. The bounce that Rankin was extracting means that it takes the outside edge and the keeper gets another dismissal added to his name

dismissalText.commentary: Tim Murtagh c Mire b Cremer 4 (9b 0x4 0x6 9m) SR: 44.44

commentTextItems.html: Zimbabwe move to the top of the table. Fuller ball on the off stump. He comes down the track and lofts it deep midwicket where the catch is taken.

commentPostTextItems.html: Thanks for joining us today and for the participation through your comments. Do keep joining us for the remaining matches in the tournament. Before we leave one more thought on this game. It's by Trevor. He says, "Really pleased with the performance by Zimbabwe today. Certainly not their best but at least for my sake, there was no need for meds for those heart racing moments." Good night from all of us here and if you missed the match, please read the report by Deivarayan Muthu

Cremer: Bit nervous at half-time. We thought if we could get over 200 it was tough to chase. We thought we didn't have enough. Sikandar is man of the match. He stuck it out with the tail and that's tough. Crowd is huge for us. They keep turning out wherever we are. I hope they continue to do the same
Porterfield: We let ourselves down. We were confident at half-time.

Sikandar Raza is the Player of the match. He had this to say "I cannot believe this. When I got back to rooms after halfway stage, my head was down. My teammates said this was enough, we can fight. I was wanting to have a partnership but ran out Craig (Ervine). Blessing (Muzarabani) hanging out there was good. This trophy is presented to me, but it belongs to all of us. The crowd is actually the 12th man here "

At 26.6 overs in both the innings, there was a run-out. For both the teams it was their sixth wicket that went down. While Zimbabwe dug deep and added 99 runs to the total after the fall of sixth wicket, Ireland capitulated - losing their last 4 wickets 18 runs. Inexcusable really if you see they added a batsman to their team.

headshotImage.longCaption: Barry McCarthy player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Sean Williams c McCarthy b Murtagh 9 (15b 0x4 0x6 32m) SR: 60

dismissalComment.html: short ball outside the off stump. Williams was set up for the shot that he played - pull. He lofts it to McCarthy at deep midwicket. He didn't need to run a lot to take the catch. That's poor awareness of the match situation by Williams. When a fielder is placed for exactly that shot, one should get their eye in before thinking of clearing that fielder. Also the pace of Murtagh is such that Williams had to impart a lot of power on his own to get it over the ropes

dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor lbw b McBrine 25 (41b 1x4 1x6 54m) SR: 60.97

dismissalComment.html: fuller ball outside the off stump and turning this time. Taylor looks to reverse sweep and is beaten. He is struck on the hip. It might have been going down leg as he stretched out his frontfoot. The wicket leaves Zimbabwe tottering  and in need of a partnership

dismissalText.commentary: Craig Ervine run out (†NJ O'Brien) 20 (26b 2x4 1x6 45m) SR: 76.92

dismissalComment.html: good length on the middle and leg. He defends it uncomfortably to the leg side and for some reason, they want to take a single. Maybe Sikandar is wary of Rankin after getting hit on the glove as well. Niall O'Brien runs forward and throws it to Stirling who lifts the bails off in time as Ervine was just a few millimeters away from the crease. That's poor judgement of a run by Sikandar.

dismissalText.commentary: Graeme Cremer b KJ O'Brien 4 (23b 0x4 0x6 26m) SR: 17.39

dismissalComment.html: Kevin O'Brien sneaks through the defences of Cremer. He sends the leg stump cartwheeling. This was nice and full, jabs back in just enough to nip through the gate and knock out the leg stump

headshotImage.longCaption: Tendai Chisoro player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: William Porterfield c Sikandar Raza b Chisoro 7 (11b 1x4 0x6 15m) SR: 63.63

dismissalComment.html: and that's the first wicket! Short ball on the middle stump. Porterfield doesn't account for Chisoro's pace. He is faster than an average left arm spinner and looks to pull. All he does is guide it into the hands of Sikandar Raza at short midwicket

dismissalText.commentary: Paul Stirling run out (Sikandar Raza) 41 (70b 5x4 0x6 100m) SR: 58.57

dismissalComment.html: what a co-incidence! Zimbabwe and Ireland both have a run-out on 26.6 overs! Good length ball outside the off stump. Stirling defends it to the off side and sets off for what he deems to be a single. Wilson refuses but Stirling is close to Wilson then the stumps. So, it's obvious that Stirling would be struggling. He is couple of feet out. Ervine was out on 26.6 over for Zimbabwe

headshotImage.caption: Kyle Jarvis player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Kyle Jarvis player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Andy Balbirnie c †Taylor b Jarvis 2 (14b 0x4 0x6 14m) SR: 14.28

dismissalComment.html: that's the second wicket! Short of a good length delivery outside the off stump and coming in. The ball takes the inside edge. Taylor dives to his left and takes the catch. Zimbabwe bowling is coming to the party

headshotImage.caption: Tendai Chisoro player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Tendai Chisoro player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Ed Joyce st †Taylor b Chisoro 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 5m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: and that's the third wicket! It hits the thigh pad and Joyce is looking for an opportunity to run a leg bye , but doesn't realise that Taylor has collected the ball. He just steps out of the crease and Taylor whups the bails off. Joyce doesn't even wait for third umpire's decision

dismissalText.commentary: Niall O'Brien c Muzarabani b Chisoro 8 (14b 1x4 0x6 16m) SR: 57.14

dismissalComment.html: it has to be the fielder's wicket! Short on the middle and leg. Niall is looking to pull and gets a top-edge. The ball looks to be in the gap between short fine-leg and square-leg. Muzarabani, at short fine-leg, takes a few strides forward and then moves sideways. When he realises that he can't get to the ball by running, he dives and catches the ball inches off the ground.

dismissalText.commentary: Kevin O'Brien c Masakadza b Williams 7 (15b 1x4 0x6 16m) SR: 46.66

dismissalComment.html: and gets a wicket with the second ball! Good length ball outside the off stump. Kevin is playing for the angle but the ball turns after pitching and takes the outside edge. First slip moves to the left and takes the catch

dismissalText.commentary: Gary Wilson lbw b Cremer 15 (41b 1x4 0x6 42m) SR: 36.58

dismissalComment.html: good length ball on the middle stump. He is playing for the ripping leg break and misses. He knows as he has played it that he is plumb in front. Ireland slip deeper now

stories.seoTitle: Della Penna: The painfully small margins in Associate cricket
stories.summary: Nepal has gained ODI status for the first time winning absolute nail-biters, but the teams that lost by such small margins also deserve a shot at more funding and better recognition
